    Create Single port RAM General Method wf.png
    
    continued with memory implementation and built a single-port ram with write enable using the general rtl method. unlike combinational logic where outputs are derived directly from inputs, memory introduces state. the design stores data at a selected address when write enable is asserted and retrieves data from the same memory array when write enable is deasserted.
    
    the key constraint of a single-port ram is that read and write operations share the same port. only one operation can occur during a clock cycle. if write enable is high, the memory performs a write operation. if write enable is low, the memory performs a read operation. both operations use the same address path and memory resource, which keeps the implementation compact and resource-efficient compared to dual-port or multi-port memory architectures.
    
    at this stage, the implementation works and the waveform verifies the expected behavior. however, the focus now is less on getting the module functional and more on understanding how to structure it better. questions such as synchronous vs asynchronous reads, parameterizing memory depth and width, inference of block ram vs distributed ram, and writing synthesizer-friendly rtl are more interesting than the basic implementation itself. the current version follows the lecture approach. the next step is to experiment with alternative implementations and understand the tradeoffs behind each design choice rather than treating the module as a fixed template.

