    memories
    
    moved into memory implementation in verilog. learned the two primary memory resources available in an fpga: block ram and distributed ram. both can be used to implement rom structures, while ram implementations are inferred based on the coding style, size requirements, and synthesis decisions.
    
    also went through the three common implementation approaches: general rtl coding, vendor-provided language templates, and ip-based block design. each provides a different level of abstraction and control over the final hardware.
    
    now the goal is to learn to implement a single-port ram using the general method first. before using templates or ips, i want to understand how the memory array, addressing logic, read operation, and write operation are described directly in rtl and how synthesis maps them to physical memory resources on the fpga.

